{
  "text": "Hemiplegia/hemiparesis is a common complication of stroke. It is often worsened by the presence of hemiplegic shoulder pain (HSP)/post-stroke shoulder pain (PSSP) [CITATION_1] . Ultrasonography (USS) is advantageous over other imaging methods that have been used in evaluating the shoulder. Its advantages include broad availability, cost-effectiveness, real-time imaging, direct multiplanar assessment, immediate side-to-side comparison, short examination time, and lack of ionizing radiation) [CITATION_2] . Furthermore, it closely rivals shoulder magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) in accurately diagnosing full thickness rotator cuff tears [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] and has been shown to be preferred to MRI by patients with shoulder pain [CITATION_5] .",
